1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,040
Let's start this new investigation right away; today we are diving into a real economic mystery.

2
00:00:05,040 --> 00:00:06,040
mystery.

3
00:00:06,040 --> 00:00:10,080
Usually when we think about finance and interest rates, we imagine a world

4
00:00:10,080 --> 00:00:13,759
made of cold, objective, and absolutely impartial numbers.

5
00:00:13,759 --> 00:00:18,359
The common idea is that the credit market doesn't look at anyone's face, but limits itself

6
00:00:18,359 --> 00:00:20,160
to evaluating financial statements and guarantees.

7
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:25,560
Yet, a truly fascinating study by Alesina, Lotti, and Mistrulli, based on real

8
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:29,719
Italian data, raises a crucial question, which is exactly the title of

9
00:00:29,719 --> 00:00:34,460
our analysis: Do banks discriminate against women? Let's dive straight into the data to

10
00:00:34,460 --> 00:00:37,280
try to understand what is really happening.

11
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:42,200
To understand the gravity of the situation, we must start from the body of the crime, so to speak.

12
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:46,480
The data shows us unequivocally that female entrepreneurs, with equal initial

13
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:50,560
conditions, pay a significantly higher premium to access credit.

14
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:54,359
We are talking about a full 28 basis points more than their male colleagues.

15
00:00:54,359 --> 00:00:59,679
28 might seem like little, but in reality, on a normal line of credit for a micro-enterprise, this

16
00:00:59,679 --> 00:01:03,600
gap translates instantly into hundreds of euros of additional costs every single

17
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:08,120
year. It is literally an invisible tax that weighs solely and exclusively on female-led

18
00:01:08,120 --> 00:01:09,120
businesses.

19
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:11,280
But where does this difference come from?

20
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:14,560
Is it just a cold question of risk, or is there something else going on?

21
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:21,400
Okay, let's get into the heart of it and examine the first suspect in this investigation: financial

22
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:29,240
risk. That is, answering the question: are women by any chance less reliable debtors?

23
00:01:29,239 --> 00:01:33,299
The most logical explanation, the one that would come to mind for any analyst, is that

24
00:01:33,299 --> 00:01:37,560
women pay higher rates simply because their businesses are considered

25
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:39,640
intrinsically riskier.

26
00:01:39,640 --> 00:01:45,359
Well, prepare to discard this hypothesis, because the data refutes it all along the line.

27
00:01:45,359 --> 00:01:50,000
Looking at the metrics, the insolvency rate—that is, the frequency with which they fail to

28
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,560
repay debts or go bankrupt—is 0.5% for men and 0.4% for

29
00:01:56,560 --> 00:01:57,560
women.

30
00:01:57,560 --> 00:02:02,280
Surprise: women go bankrupt less. And that's not all; also the use of credit lines

31
00:02:02,280 --> 00:02:10,599
shows a practically identical management, 73.9% versus 75.2%. In short, the hypothesis of financial

32
00:02:10,599 --> 00:02:12,719
risk collapses miserably.

33
00:02:12,719 --> 00:02:16,520
Women are not at all more dangerous customers for banks.

34
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:22,039
Let's move on then to the second suspect: what if it simply depends on the choice of the

35
00:02:22,039 --> 00:02:26,439
bank? Maybe it's just a question of where one goes to ask for this loan.

36
00:02:26,960 --> 00:02:31,319
It is a more than legitimate question; one might think that female entrepreneurs end up

37
00:02:31,319 --> 00:02:36,800
turning to credit institutions that are on average more expensive for everyone. But pay attention,

38
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:38,840
because here the plot thickens.

39
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:44,039
The researchers applied very strict statistical filters to isolate the different banks,

40
00:02:44,039 --> 00:02:48,680
and the result is jaw-dropping: the cost gap remains identical even within

41
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:50,599
the exact same bank.

42
00:02:50,599 --> 00:02:55,000
Same institution, same branch, but different rates for men and women with completely

43
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,479
equal risk profiles. So no, it's not a question of having chosen the wrong bank;

44
00:02:59,479 --> 00:03:02,680
it is a systematic behavior within the single branch.

45
00:03:02,680 --> 00:03:08,319
And this brings us to a real twist, what we can call the paradox of the

46
00:03:08,319 --> 00:03:12,840
guarantors, an absolutely crucial clue in our investigation.

47
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:18,199
As we well know, when a bank turns up its nose at a loan, it asks for a guarantor,

48
00:03:18,199 --> 00:03:23,520
someone who puts their own assets as collateral. Now, analyzing the gender of these

49
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:26,320
guarantors, something incredible emerges.

50
00:03:26,320 --> 00:03:31,840
If a woman presents herself with a male guarantor, the bank breathes a sigh of relief, and the interest

51
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:33,160
rate goes down.

52
00:03:33,160 --> 00:03:39,439
But pay attention, if the same woman presents herself with a female guarantor, pay attention, the interest

53
00:03:39,439 --> 00:03:41,600
rate rises dizzyingly.

54
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:47,000
A woman guaranteed by another woman automatically becomes the most penalized customer

55
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:52,640
in the entire market, arriving to pay almost 30 basis points more than

56
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:56,040
a man without any guarantor. Crazy, right?

57
00:03:56,040 --> 00:04:00,080
Arrived at this point, the classic rules of economics seem to leak from all

58
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:01,080
sides.

59
00:04:01,080 --> 00:04:05,800
Let's recap: we have established that women are super reliable debtors, even

60
00:04:05,800 --> 00:04:06,800
more so than men.

61
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:11,600
We have seen that the disparity occurs within the same bank, and we have

62
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:17,120
discovered that two women who ally financially suffer the worst penalty of all.

63
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:21,400
If market rationality and traditional economic models cannot explain

64
00:04:21,399 --> 00:04:24,359
this mystery, what is the real cause of all this?

65
00:04:24,359 --> 00:04:30,279
And here we unmask the first real culprit: cultural prejudice, which feeds

66
00:04:30,279 --> 00:04:33,519
on traditional conventions about the world of work.

67
00:04:33,519 --> 00:04:37,560
In economics, this phenomenon is called taste-based discrimination.

68
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:42,000
In practice, rationality is thrown out the window to be guided by gender

69
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
prejudice. And to understand how deeply rooted this thing is, just analyze the data from the World

70
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Value Survey for Italy.

71
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,720
The survey asks if one agrees with the phrase: when jobs are scarce, men

72
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:55,360
have more right to a job than women.

73
00:05:00,160 --> 00:05:03,720
Observing the data, while Sweden has very low levels and the United States is mid-table,

74
00:05:03,720 --> 00:05:07,959
Italy records the highest level in absolute among advanced countries.

75
00:05:07,959 --> 00:05:11,480
This is a deep belief that permeates the entire society, and which inevitably

76
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:16,199
sits at the table with whoever has to decide whether to grant a loan.

77
00:05:16,199 --> 00:05:20,479
The authors of the study go straight to the point and formulate a very clear hypothesis: bank

78
00:05:16,199 --> 00:05:20,479
directors might simply consider women as less desirable clients,

79
00:05:20,479 --> 00:05:24,360
regardless of their perfect financial statements, for the sole fact of being women.

80
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:27,639
The definitive proof comes by looking at the various economic sectors.

81
00:05:27,639 --> 00:05:31,680
In fields historically dominated by men like construction or heavy industry,

82
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:35,560
this penalty for women reaches record levels, as if the system cast

83
00:05:35,560 --> 00:05:38,279
doubt on female competence in those contexts.

84
00:05:38,279 --> 00:05:42,519
On the contrary, in sectors perceived as more feminine, such as retail trade,

85
00:05:42,519 --> 00:05:46,159
this difference in interest rates narrows until it almost disappears.

86
00:05:46,159 --> 00:05:51,680
We are still missing the last piece of the puzzle, the second culprit: bargaining power

87
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:54,359
and negotiation dynamics under stress.

88
00:05:54,359 --> 00:05:58,719
Because, if we think about it, getting a loan is not like buying an object with a

89
00:05:58,719 --> 00:05:59,719
fixed price.

90
00:05:59,719 --> 00:06:05,120
It is a process; one must bargain and negotiate, and behavioral economics teaches that

91
00:06:05,120 --> 00:06:09,799
in high-stress situations, whoever has more bargaining power gets the better end.

92
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:13,879
Analyzing the data on Italian bank managers in the period studied, the situation is

93
00:06:13,879 --> 00:06:19,280
to say the least illuminating: less than 10% of decision-making positions are occupied by women.

94
00:06:19,280 --> 00:06:24,360
Over 90% of the officers, those who materially decided, were men.

95
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:26,920
This creates a resounding power imbalance.

96
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:30,720
A female entrepreneur systematically finds herself having to defend her project in an

97
00:06:30,720 --> 00:06:35,920
environment dominated by male figures, a dynamic that makes the negotiation much tougher,

98
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:39,000
and actively contributes to maintaining higher rates.

99
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,240
Drawing the threads of this spectacular investigation, the picture we face is as

100
00:06:43,240 --> 00:06:47,120
fascinating from an academic perspective as it is harsh for the real economy.

101
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:52,120
Let's recap the facts: one, women pay more; two, paradoxically they are not at all

102
00:06:52,120 --> 00:06:57,040
riskier clients; three, even financial solidarity among women, with a female guarantor,

103
00:06:57,040 --> 00:07:00,680
is penalized by the system. And why does all this happen?

104
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:04,660
The answer is not in finance textbooks, but in an invisible mix made of deep-rooted

105
00:07:04,660 --> 00:07:08,860
cultural prejudices and a chronic lack of diversity in the decision-making rooms

106
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:12,820
of banks, a lethal mix that inflates costs dramatically.

107
00:07:12,820 --> 00:07:18,220
And this awareness leaves us with a final great provocation: if the credit market

108
00:07:18,220 --> 00:07:23,060
is not that perfect, super-rational machine studied at university,

109
00:07:23,060 --> 00:07:28,260
but ends up absorbing all the prejudices of the society in which it lives, the challenge is clear:

110
00:07:28,260 --> 00:07:32,940
it is not enough to show up with perfect accounts to obtain equal treatment;

111
00:07:32,939 --> 00:07:37,980
we must dismantle those invisible barriers made of cultural legacies and power imbalances.

112
00:07:37,980 --> 00:07:42,219
The real question, the one with which today's reflection closes, is this:

113
00:07:42,219 --> 00:07:47,100
What actions must be taken now, so that in the future the solidity of a business idea

114
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:52,220
is finally priced only for its absolute merit, and not for the gender of the person proposing it?
